CrowdAuth in FishEye needlessly asks remote Crowd for the SSO cookie token name each time it validates a user.

This can easily be avoided by setting the default cookie token name in the client properties when setting up the Crowd Client in the Crowd Auth. This will break users who have a non-default token name set.

If a user has changed the SSO token name from the default, they will need to override it by adding the following property to the properties string in the Crowd Auth config in FishEye admin:
{code}
cookie.tokenkey=MY_SSO_COOKIE_TOKEN_KEY
{code}

When OAuth is being used in the Application Link between FishEye and JIRA, the Smart Commit to transition / comment on a JIRA issue will fail if the committer hadn't previously created his consumer token from FishEye side to JIRA side. 
My commit message:
{noformat}
JRA-1 #close #comment Fixing a bug
{noformat}

This Smart Commit was not executed. The JIRA issue was not transitioned and a comment was not added to it.

One can only see what happened if FishEye was in *debug mode*:
{noformat}
2013-06-13 14:27:04,732 DEBUG [CommitNotifier1 ] fisheye JiraIssueServiceImpl-logException - Error retrieving issue 'JRA-1' from JIRA server at http://localhost:8080/browse/JRA-1
com.atlassian.applinks.api.CredentialsRequiredException: You do not have an authorized access token for the remote resource.
{noformat}

Customers don't keep debug mode ON, so they won't know what happened by investigating the logs. This DEBUG message could be turned into a WARN.

Also, to make it even more clear for customers, a span/banner could be added to the FishEye web interface mentioning this problem. This would better not be placed in the administration panel, because not all FishEye users are administrators, and the token must be created for each user.

For Perforce repositories, getAuthor returns the userId where as for Stash repos, it returns the displayName.

Here is a sample code in the Fisheye commit listener.

{code}
@EventListener
public void onCommit(CommitEvent event) {
	String repoName = event.getRepositoryName();

	String changeSetId = event.getChangeSetId();
	ChangesetDataFE cs = revisionDataService.getChangeset(repoName, changeSetId);
	String author = cs.getAuthor();
}
{code}

Can you make it consistent across repos so that the plugin developers can build the User URL from it?

Paragraph text currently states that, {quote}"Mappings can be deleted from the Project Repository Path Mapping section of the [FishEye Configuration|http://localhost:8080/secure/admin/ViewFishEyeConfig.jspa] screen.
{quote}

That linked page doesn't have that section and I haven't found any page with this section. Furthermore, the only place to delete this kind of mapping is from the project's own profile page. I've attached some screenshots for clarity.

FishEye behaves strangely when indexing (SVN) files with non-printable characters in their filenames. The characters are converted as UTF and the indexing stops.

The following can be seen in the logs:
{noformat}
Repository paused due to error com.cenqua.fisheye.rep.DbException: Problem getting diff information for rev120500 com.cenqua.fisheye.svn.diff.SvnDiffException: Exception processing diff for revision 120500 com.cenqua.fisheye.rep.RepositoryClientException: org.tigris.subversion.javahl.ClientException: svn: E170000: URL 'https://www.acme.com/svn/repos/wcoyote/components/rrunner-catcher/trunk/src/main/unix/scripts/exit%0A' non-existent in revision 120,500 org.tigris.subversion.javahl.ClientException: svn: E170000: URL 'https://www.acme.com/svn/repos/wcoyote/components/rrunner-catcher/trunk/src/main/unix/scripts/exit%0A' non-existent in revision 120,500 org.tmatesoft.svn.core.SVNException: svn: E170000: URL 'https://www.acme.com/svn/repos/wcoyote/components/rrunner-catcher/trunk/src/main/unix/scripts/exit%0A' non-existent in revision 120,500

{noformat}
Note "%0A" at the end of the filename.

At present if smart commits are being used, the commit is added to Fisheye with the smart commit commands included in it. For eg:
{noformat}
Commit comment JRA-1 #resolve #time 2d 5h #comment Task completed
{noformat}
It would be good to parse the commit commands from the actual commit message, to have something like:
{noformat}
Commit comment JRA-1
{noformat}

